You are building a production-minded Node.js + TypeScript scraper for Swedish Large Cap company annual report extraction.

NON-NEGOTIABLE CONSTRAINTS:
- Public websites only. No API keys.
- Use cheerio for HTML parsing as the primary method.
- Use pdf-parse for PDF text extraction.
- Script must run with: npx ts-node scrape.ts
- Output must be a structured results.json.
- The system accepts ANY 10 Swedish Large Cap companies as input — it is NOT hardcoded to a specific list. Company selection is a runtime parameter.
- Different companies have different site structures. Discovery and extraction must be dynamic and heuristic-driven, not site-specific templates.
- Add robust logging, timeout handling, retry limits, missing-PDF handling, and parsing-failure handling.
- Prefer stable architecture over cleverness.
- Never make large speculative edits without stating the plan first.

BEFORE ANY EDIT, explain:
1) what files you will create/change
2) why
3) what success criteria you will validate

AFTER ANY EDIT, run tests or executable checks where possible and summarize failures.

WORKING STYLE:
- Keep functions small and named clearly.
- Separate discovery, download, extraction, normalization, and persistence into distinct modules.
- Build for reruns and partial reruns.
- Use deterministic heuristics as the primary extraction method, but when heuristics fail or produce ambiguous results, use web search (Bing), multi-domain resolution, or other creative discovery methods as fallbacks. The goal is zero failed rows for listed Large Cap companies.
- When uncertain about an extracted VALUE, return null with an explanation — never fabricate a value.
- When uncertain about DISCOVERY (finding the right PDF), be aggressive — try multiple domains, search engines, URL patterns, and external sources before giving up.
- Optimize for a repo that can be shown to a demanding technical evaluator.

COMPANY INPUT MODEL:
- A "company profile" is a runtime object with: name, ticker, website URL, optional IR path hints, optional candidateDomains, companyType, orgNumber, and knownAliases.
- A default registry of 10 companies ships with the project, but the architecture must support swapping in any other Swedish Large Cap company by editing a single config file or passing CLI arguments.
- Company-specific logic is confined to the profile config — the pipeline code itself is company-agnostic.

PLAYWRIGHT FALLBACK POLICY:
- cheerio is the primary and default HTML parser for all companies.
- Playwright is an OPTIONAL fallback for JS-rendered pages. It must be an optional dependency — the project must work without it installed.
- If a company profile indicates JS-rendered content (e.g., jsRendered: true or previous runs failed with 0 PDF links from cheerio), Playwright may be tried EARLIER in the fallback ladder — not necessarily last.
- If Playwright is not available at runtime, skip gracefully and continue to the next fallback.
- In logs, always indicate when Playwright is being used: "[Company] Falling back to Playwright for JS-rendered content"

DISCOVERY PHILOSOPHY:
- The goal is to find every listed Large Cap company's annual report. A "failed" status for a company that publishes an annual report is a bug, not an acceptable outcome.
- Discovery should work even when the company website cannot be resolved. Direct PDF search via Bing, multi-domain resolution, allabolag org-number lookup, and external financial data sources are all valid fallback paths.
- When orgNumber is available in the company profile, always try the allabolag direct URL (https://www.allabolag.se/{orgNumberWithoutHyphen}) — do not rely on name search.
DOMAIN RESOLUTION:
- The pipeline must resolve any Swedish Large Cap company to its correct website from just a name or ticker. It must NOT depend on pre-configured domains to function.
- ticker.json candidateDomains are a performance cache, not a dependency. The pipeline must work without them.
- When inferring domains from company names, use the legal/brand name (e.g., "Ericsson" from "Telefonaktiebolaget LM Ericsson"), not the ticker slug (e.g., "ERIC"). Ticker slugs produce wrong domains (eric.se, hmb.se, telepathy.com).
- Validate inferred domains: reject any domain that doesn't contain a recognizable word from the company name.
- When domain inference fails, fall back to search engine queries ("{company name} investor relations site") before giving up.

GIT DISCIPLINE:
- Commit after every successful fix: git add -A && git commit -m "fix: [description]"
- Never leave working code uncommitted across sessions.